iptables
--------
  A linux firewall tool used to control network traffic (Allow/Block/filter)

 Core Concepts
 > Tables
  | Table  | Purpose                          |
  |--------|----------------------------------|
  | filter | Default → allow/block traffic    |
  | nat    | Network Address Translation      |
  | mangle | Modify packets                   |

  > Chains
  | Chain   | Meaning                     |
  |---------|-----------------------------|
  | INPUT   | Incoming traffic            |
  | OUTPUT  | Outgoing traffic            |
  | FORWARD | Passing through server      |

  > Actions (Targets)
  | Action | Meaning              |
  |--------|----------------------|
  | ACCEPT | Allow traffic        |
  | DROP   | Block silently       |
  | REJECT | Block with response  |

Difference between iptables and AWS Security Groups? 
  Both controls traffic but they work at different layer of your system
  * AWS Security Group:- Virtual firewall at cloud network level. Works outside your EC2 instance at AWS infrastructure level
  * iptables:- Firewall inside your EC2 instance (OS level). Inside linux operating system. Controls packets at kernel level

# Hands-on: Observe when Security group allows but iptables blocks

o Run a web server on port 8080
o Allow port 8080 in Security Groups
o Block port 8080 using iptables
o Test access from browser

Step 1: Start Web server
python3 -m http.server 8080
Step 2: Verify inside EC2 (localhost)
curl localhost:8080

Verify (browser):

http://<EC2-public-ip>:8080

Note: Ensure security group is allowing the traffic on port 8080

Step 3: Apply iptables Block
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 8080 -j DROP

-A INPUT : apply to incoming traffic
-p tcp: protocol
--dport 8080: target port
-j DROP: silently block

Step 4: Test Again

From Browser

http://<EC2-Public-IP>:8080

o Page will not load
o Timeout/connection refused

Inside EC2 (From Localhost)

curl localhost:8080

Connection refused

Root cause: iptables is blocking all the traffic even from localhost

Step 5: If want to allow traffic inside localhost
sudo iptables -I INPUT 1 -i lo -j ACCEPT
Step 6: Revert the changes
sudo iptables -D INPUT -p tcp --dport 8080 -j DROP
Common Network Security Attacks (e.g., DDoS, Man-in-the-Middle)
DDOS (Distributed Denial of Service)

Flood a server with massive traffic -> make it unavailable

How it works

o Thousands of compromised machines (botnet)
o Send requests simultaneously
o Server resources exhausted

Detection

o Sudden spike in traffic
o High CPU/Memory usage
o Many requests from different Ips

Prevention

o Load balancers
o AWS Shield
o Use Cloudflare (CDN + Security layer)
o Rate limiting (Restricts number of requests per user/IP in a time window)

MITM (Man-in-the-Middle)

Attacks secretly intercept communication

Example:
User -> Attacker -> Server

Detection

o Unexpected certificate warnings
o Suspicious network behavior

Prevention

o HTTPS (SSL/TLS)
o VPN
o Secure Wi-fi

Malware/Ransomware

Malicious software infects system

Effect

o Data theft
o File encryption

Prevention

o Antivirus
o Regular updates
o Backup

Phishing

Fake emails/websites to steal credentials

Detection

o Suspicious link
o Fake domain

Prevention

o Use awareness
o Email filtering

Access Control Lists (ACLs) and Firewall Rules

An Access Control list (ACL) is
A set of rules that allow or deny traffic based on IP, protocol, port

Where ACLs are used

o Network devices (routers, switches)
o Cloud (AWS Network ACLs)
o Operating System (file ACLs also exist)

Example Rule:

ALLOW 192.168.1.0/24
DENY 0.0.0.0/0

Note:
o Allow internal network
o Deny everything else

How ACL works

o Rules are checked from top -> bottom
o First match is applied
o If no match -> default action (allow/deny)

What are Firewall Rules?

Firewall rules are instructions that controls incoming and outgoing traffic

Example:

sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
ACL vs Firewall Rules

Feature ACL Firewall
Level Network OS/Cloud
Type Stateless Stateful
Rule Order Strict order Can be flexible
Complexity Basic Advanced

